Q5. In a machine learning project, you have a dataset with 1000 rows and 5 columns. Two of the columns
are categorical, and the remaining three columns are numerical. If you were to use nominal encoding to
transform the categorical data, how many new columns would be created? Show your calculations.
Ans:
If we use nominal encoding to transform two categorical columns with 5 unique values each, you would create a new column for each categorical column. This would result in 2 new columns.
___________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________________

Q6. You are working with a dataset containing information about different types of animals, including their
species, habitat, and diet. Which encoding technique would you use to transform the categorical data into
a format suitable for machine learning algorithms? Justify your answer.
Ans:
For this scenario, you would likely use one-hot encoding. One-hot encoding creates binary columns for each unique category within a categorical feature. Since "species," "habitat," and "diet" are not ordinal and don't have any inherent numeric relationships, one-hot encoding ensures that the machine learning algorithm doesn't misinterpret the encoded values as having meaningful order or magnitude.
